The term "sabertoothed" seems to be one that paleontologists disagree about. Strictly speaking there was one family of felines that diverged from the common ancestors of modern small and large cats before small and large cats diverged from one another. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Machairodontinae has more about them than you want to know. Is an elephant a sabertoothed creature? Its tusks are teeth. Wild boars also have tusk teeth but I do not hear of anyone calling them "sabertooth pigs." Typically the term is only applied to that one family of extinct felines, the last species of which seem to have gone extinct between ten thousand and twelve thousand-ish years back.
